---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';

const faq = [
  { question: "What is AWS CDK and how does it differ from CloudFormation?", answer: "AWS CDK (Cloud Development Kit) is an open-source framework that lets you define cloud infrastructure using familiar programming languages like TypeScript, Python, Java, C#, and Go. Under the hood, CDK synthesizes your code into CloudFormation templates. The key difference is developer experience: instead of writing hundreds of lines of YAML, you write type-safe, object-oriented code with IDE auto-completion, loops, conditionals, and abstractions. CDK Constructs are reusable building blocks that encapsulate best practices, making CDK far more productive than raw CloudFormation." },
  { question: "What are L1, L2, and L3 constructs in AWS CDK?", answer: "CDK organizes constructs into three levels. L1 (CloudFormation Resources, prefixed with Cfn) are auto-generated direct mappings to CloudFormation resources — they expose every property but require you to configure everything. L2 constructs are handcrafted abstractions with sensible defaults, type-safe properties, and helper methods (e.g., s3.Bucket, lambda.Function). L3 constructs (also called Patterns) are higher-level solutions that compose multiple L2 constructs, like aws-ecs-patterns.ApplicationLoadBalancedFargateService, which wires up ECS, ALB, IAM, and more automatically." },
  { question: "How do I deploy a CDK app to AWS?", answer: "First run cdk bootstrap to provision the CDK Toolkit stack in your account (one-time per account/region). Then run cdk synth to generate the CloudFormation template and review it. Run cdk diff to see exactly what changes will be made versus what is currently deployed. Finally run cdk deploy to provision or update resources. You can deploy specific stacks with cdk deploy MyStack or all stacks with cdk deploy --all. For CI/CD, use CDK Pipelines which automates synthesis, testing, and multi-stage deployment." },
  { question: "What is cdk diff and why is it important?", answer: "cdk diff compares your synthesized template against the currently deployed CloudFormation stack and shows a detailed diff of added, modified, and removed resources. This is critical for safety — it lets you review exactly what will change before deploying, similar to terraform plan. Pay special attention to replacements (shown in red): some resource changes (like renaming a DynamoDB table) require destroying and recreating the resource, which means data loss. Always run cdk diff before cdk deploy in production." },
  { question: "How does CDK handle secrets and sensitive configuration?", answer: "CDK itself does not store secrets. The recommended pattern is to use AWS Secrets Manager or AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store to store secrets, then reference them in your CDK code using SecretValue.secretsManager() or ssm.StringParameter.valueForStringParameter(). This keeps secrets out of your source code and CDK templates. For environment-specific configuration, use CDK context values (cdk.json or --context flags) for non-sensitive data, and never hardcode credentials in stacks." },
  { question: "What is CDK Pipelines and when should I use it?", answer: "CDK Pipelines is a high-level construct library for building continuous delivery pipelines using AWS CodePipeline. It automates the entire release process: source checkout, CDK synthesis, unit tests, deployment to multiple stages (dev/staging/prod), and integration tests between stages. You should use CDK Pipelines when you want self-mutating pipelines (the pipeline updates itself when you push changes to its definition), multi-account deployments, or a GitOps-style workflow where merging to main automatically triggers deployments." },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="AWS CDK Guide — Infrastructure as Code with Real Programming Languages"
  description="Complete guide to AWS CDK: constructs, stacks, TypeScript examples, CDK Pipelines, and comparison with Terraform, CloudFormation, Pulumi, and SAM. Free reference for cloud engineers."
  tool="AWS CDK, Cloud Development Kit, infrastructure as code, CDK constructs, CDK TypeScript, CDK vs Terraform"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebPage",
    "name": "AWS CDK Guide — Infrastructure as Code with Real Programming Languages",
    "url": "https://devplaybook.cc/tools/aws-cdk-guide",
    "description": "Complete guide to AWS CDK: constructs, stacks, TypeScript examples, CDK Pipelines, and comparison with Terraform, CloudFormation, Pulumi, and SAM.",
  })} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">AWS CDK Guide</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">
    Define AWS infrastructure using <strong>real programming languages</strong> — TypeScript, Python, Java, C#, or Go.
    AWS CDK synthesizes your code into CloudFormation and deploys it with a single command.
  </p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> TypeScript / Python / Java / C# / Go</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> L1 / L2 / L3 Constructs</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> CDK Pipelines CI/CD</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> cdk diff safety checks</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">What is AWS CDK?</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4 leading-relaxed">
    AWS Cloud Development Kit (CDK) is an open-source infrastructure-as-code framework that lets you define cloud resources using general-purpose programming languages instead of YAML or JSON. Released by AWS in 2019 and now at v2, CDK compiles your code into CloudFormation templates during a synthesis step, then uses CloudFormation's battle-tested engine to provision and update resources. This means you get all the safety guarantees of CloudFormation (drift detection, rollbacks, change sets) plus the developer ergonomics of modern languages: type safety, IDE auto-complete, loops, conditionals, unit tests, and package management via npm or pip.
  </p>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4 leading-relaxed">
    The core abstraction in CDK is the <strong>Construct</strong> — a reusable cloud component that can represent a single resource (like an S3 bucket) or a complex pattern (like a load-balanced ECS service with autoscaling, logging, and IAM). Constructs are organized into <strong>Stacks</strong>, which map 1:1 to CloudFormation stacks. Stacks live inside an <strong>App</strong>, the root of every CDK project.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Key Features</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-muted space-y-1 mb-4 ml-2">
    <li><strong>Constructs Library</strong> — 300+ L2 constructs with secure defaults and helper methods (grant*, metric*, addToPolicy)</li>
    <li><strong>L1 / L2 / L3 Construct Levels</strong> — raw CloudFormation → opinionated abstractions → full architectural patterns</li>
    <li><strong>cdk synth / diff / deploy</strong> — synthesize templates, preview changes, and deploy with one command</li>
    <li><strong>CDK Pipelines</strong> — self-mutating CI/CD pipelines with multi-stage, multi-account deployments</li>
    <li><strong>Assets</strong> — bundle Lambda code, Docker images, and S3 files automatically during synthesis</li>
    <li><strong>Escape Hatches</strong> — override any CloudFormation property via addOverride() when needed</li>
    <li><strong>Aspects</strong> — apply cross-cutting logic (tagging, security checks) across an entire app tree</li>
    <li><strong>Unit Testing</strong> — test infrastructure with Jest or pytest using assertions against synthesized templates</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Getting Started: Your First CDK App</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-3 leading-relaxed">Install the CDK CLI and scaffold a new TypeScript project:</p>
  <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-xs font-mono overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre text-text mb-4">npm install -g aws-cdk
cdk init app --language typescript
npm install</pre>

  <p class="text-text-muted mb-3 leading-relaxed">Define a stack with an S3 bucket and Lambda function:</p>
  <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-xs font-mono overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre text-text mb-4">// lib/my-app-stack.ts
import * as cdk from 'aws-cdk-lib';
import * as s3 from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-s3';
import * as lambda from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-lambda';
import * as s3n from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-s3-notifications';
import { Construct } from 'constructs';

export class MyAppStack extends cdk.Stack {
  constructor(scope: Construct, id: string, props?: cdk.StackProps) {
    super(scope, id, props);

    // L2 construct — S3 bucket with secure defaults
    const bucket = new s3.Bucket(this, 'DataBucket', {
      bucketName: `my-app-data-${this.account}`,
      versioned: true,
      encryption: s3.BucketEncryption.S3_MANAGED,
      blockPublicAccess: s3.BlockPublicAccess.BLOCK_ALL,
      removalPolicy: cdk.RemovalPolicy.RETAIN,
    });

    // L2 construct — Lambda function with bundled code
    const processor = new lambda.Function(this, 'Processor', {
      runtime: lambda.Runtime.NODEJS_20_X,
      handler: 'index.handler',
      code: lambda.Code.fromAsset('lambda'),
      environment: {
        BUCKET_NAME: bucket.bucketName,
      },
      timeout: cdk.Duration.seconds(30),
      memorySize: 512,
    });

    // Grant Lambda read/write access to the bucket (manages IAM automatically)
    bucket.grantReadWrite(processor);

    // Trigger Lambda on S3 object uploads
    bucket.addEventNotification(
      s3.EventType.OBJECT_CREATED,
      new s3n.LambdaDestination(processor)
    );

    // Output the bucket name
    new cdk.CfnOutput(this, 'BucketName', { value: bucket.bucketName });
  }
}</pre>

  <p class="text-text-muted mb-3 leading-relaxed">Synthesize and deploy:</p>
  <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-xs font-mono overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre text-text mb-4">cdk bootstrap aws://ACCOUNT_ID/us-east-1   # one-time setup
cdk synth                                   # generate CloudFormation template
cdk diff                                    # preview changes
cdk deploy                                  # deploy to AWS</pre>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Using L3 Pattern Constructs</h2>
  <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-xs font-mono overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre text-text mb-4">import * as ecs_patterns from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-ecs-patterns';
import * as ecs from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-ecs';
import * as ec2 from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-ec2';

// One L3 construct provisions: VPC, ECS cluster, Fargate service,
// Application Load Balancer, target group, IAM roles, CloudWatch logs
const loadBalancedService = new ecs_patterns.ApplicationLoadBalancedFargateService(
  this, 'ApiService', {
    cluster: new ecs.Cluster(this, 'Cluster', { vpc }),
    cpu: 512,
    memoryLimitMiB: 1024,
    desiredCount: 2,
    taskImageOptions: {
      image: ecs.ContainerImage.fromRegistry('nginx:latest'),
      containerPort: 80,
    },
    publicLoadBalancer: true,
  }
);

// Add autoscaling
const scaling = loadBalancedService.service.autoScaleTaskCount({ maxCapacity: 10 });
scaling.scaleOnCpuUtilization('CpuScaling', { targetUtilizationPercent: 70 });</pre>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">CDK vs Alternatives</h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse mb-6">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-bg-card">
          <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left">Feature</th>
          <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left">AWS CDK</th>
          <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left">Terraform</th>
          <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left">CloudFormation</th>
          <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left">Pulumi</th>
          <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left">SAM</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Language</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">TS / Python / Java / C# / Go</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">HCL</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">YAML / JSON</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">TS / Python / Go / .NET</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">YAML</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="bg-bg-card/30">
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Cloud support</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">AWS only</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Multi-cloud</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">AWS only</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Multi-cloud</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">AWS only (serverless)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">State management</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">CloudFormation</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">State file (S3/TFC)</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">CloudFormation</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Pulumi Service / S3</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">CloudFormation</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="bg-bg-card/30">
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Type safety</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Excellent (TypeScript)</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Good (HCL validation)</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Poor (YAML)</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Excellent</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Poor (YAML)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Learning curve</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Medium</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Low-Medium</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">High (verbose)</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Medium</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Low</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="bg-bg-card/30">
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">CI/CD integration</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">CDK Pipelines</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Terraform Cloud / Actions</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">CodePipeline</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Pulumi Deployments</td>
          <td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">SAM Pipelines</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Use Cases</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-muted space-y-1 mb-4 ml-2">
    <li>Teams already using TypeScript or Python who want IaC in the same language as their application code</li>
    <li>Complex infrastructure requiring loops, conditionals, and dynamic resource generation</li>
    <li>AWS-native shops wanting tight integration with CloudFormation, CodePipeline, and AWS services</li>
    <li>Building internal platform modules — encapsulate security baselines as reusable L3 constructs</li>
    <li>Serverless applications where CDK handles Lambda bundling, API Gateway config, and IAM permissions automatically</li>
    <li>Multi-account, multi-region deployments managed via CDK Pipelines with environment promotion gates</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Pros and Cons</h2>
  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-6">
    <div class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-green-400 mb-2">Pros</h3>
      <ul class="text-text-muted text-sm space-y-1">
        <li>✓ Full programming language expressiveness</li>
        <li>✓ IDE auto-complete and type checking catch errors early</li>
        <li>✓ Reusable constructs reduce boilerplate significantly</li>
        <li>✓ CloudFormation handles state, rollbacks, drift detection</li>
        <li>✓ Large and growing construct ecosystem (Construct Hub)</li>
        <li>✓ Unit-testable infrastructure code</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-red-400 mb-2">Cons</h3>
      <ul class="text-text-muted text-sm space-y-1">
        <li>✗ AWS-only (no Azure or GCP support)</li>
        <li>✗ CloudFormation limits apply (500 resources per stack)</li>
        <li>✗ Synthesis can be slow for very large apps</li>
        <li>✗ Breaking changes between major CDK versions</li>
        <li>✗ Harder to read for ops teams unfamiliar with programming</li>
        <li>✗ CloudFormation deployment can be slower than Terraform</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <AdUnit slot="auto" format="auto" label="Advertisement" />
  <FaqSection faq={faq} />
  <ToolPageCta currentTool="AWS CDK Guide" relatedTags={['aws', 'cdk', 'iac', 'cloud', 'infrastructure']} />
</BaseLayout>
